SIMPLE: wreathe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wreathe
<hw>Wreathe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Wreathed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wreathed</conjf>; <mark>Archaic</mark> <conjf>Wreathen</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wreathing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Wreath</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>wreath</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to revolve or writhe; to twist about; to
turn.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And from so heavy sight his head did <qex>wreathe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To twist; to convolve; to wind one about another; to
entwine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nods and smiles of recognition into which this singular
physiognomy was <qex>wreathed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From his slack hand the garland <qex>wreathed</qex> for Eve⟦br⟧
Down dropped.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To surround with anything twisted or convolved; to
encircle; to infold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each <qex>wreathed</qex> in the other's arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dusk faces with withe silken turbants <qex>wreathed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And with thy winding ivy <qex>wreathes</qex> her lance.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To twine or twist about; to surround; to
encircle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the flowers that <qex>wreathe</qex> the sparkling bowl,⟦br⟧
Fell adders hiss.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreathe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wreathe
<hw>Wreathe</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be intewoven or entwined; to
twine together; <as>as, a bower of <ex>wreathing</ex> trees</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreathen</ent>⟦br⟧
